ce:section.ce:para:
Advanced oxidation processes (AOPs) is one of the technologies which can potentially transform biorefractory compounds into non-toxic and biodegradable substances (Alpay et al., 2020). Electrochemical oxidation (EO) has received the most attention among AOPs because to high degree of oxidation performance, simplicity for operations, environmental friendliness, versatility, and cost-effectiveness (Caliari et al., 2019; Luu, 2020). Electrochemical generation of oxidants for use in water treatment includes hydrogen peroxide, free chlorine, and reactive oxygen radicals (dos Santos et al., 2020; Martínez-Huitle and Panizza, 2018; Zhou et al., 2005). When considering the oxidants that could be used in EO, free chlorine stands out as a promising alternative due to its low cost, high efficiency, and extended residual time in removing a wide range of organic contaminants. In chloride-containing electrolytes, free chlorine is produced electrochemically via the chlorine evolution anodic reaction (CER), which comprises of hypochlorous acid (HClO), dissolved chlorine (Cl2), and hypochlorite ion (ClO



                              −


                     ) (Liu et al., 2019; Park et al., 2009). It is generally accepted at this point that the activity and stability of the anode have a significant impact on EO performance.
